properties.title: Potlatch Festival Reception of the Tyee Lineup, July 17, 1912
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Golden Potlatch. July 15-20, 1912. Reception of the Tyee, July 17, 1912. 1. Joseph Blethen. 2. J.W. Spangler. 3. George Cotterill. 4. Marion E. Hay. 5. Rear Admiral Alfred Reynolds. 6. Lieutenant J.D. Little. 7. Hyas Tyee, George Allen."  From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of hte North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes," their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

properties.title: Homes on N. 76th St., east of Aurora Ave., 1953
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Houses. Row of builders' houses. North 76th Street, east of Aurora Ave. Built in the 1920's. Looking north. Photo by Werner Lenggenhager, 1953." Home at far right is 1119 N 76th St, Seattle, WA 98103. Note pasted on verso of photograph: "Row of Builders Houses. N 76th Street, just East of Aurora Avenue. South of Street facing north. 1920's. This is a group of similar, substantial, middle-income homes with their neat green lawns, evergreen shrub foundation planting, and varied roofs and porches continuing on down the street exemplified the typical Seattle neighborhood development. The white painted clapboard siding brick fireplaces, unused front yards with service, play yards and garages off the rear alley are particularly representative. The houses were obviously variations of one stock plan, fitting a certain unity to the street. They are good homes with hardwood floors, full basements and hot air heating systems. Many of today's developments still carry on in the spirit of this era, although the value of developing a more complete neighborhood environment with site developments planned for modern living, is having its influence."

Art Department, Seattle Public Library: This is a picture of part of Madison Park about 1897, one morning just before a crew race. Shown is a canoe from Johnson's Canoe Club, Paddled by Martin Martinson (living today in Ballard). The dock is a walk to the boat house, a swing, Johnson's Ice Cream Parlor, and the brick building in the background (the Pioneer Bldg). This was a the extreme south end of Madison Park. properties.title: Rainier Beach branch, Seattle Public Library, ca. 1922
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Public Library. Branches. Rainier Beach branch. 9265? 57th Ave. S." According to the "About This Branch" section of the Rainier Branch website: "Library service in Rainier Beach dates back to 1912, when The Seattle Public Library opened a deposit station at the Montera Pharmacy. The pharmacy was destroyed by fire in November 1917 and the Library lost 453 volumes valued at $428. In 1921 the Library re-established a deposit station at the Rainier Beach Dry Goods store at 9262½ 57th Ave. S., but that closed in 1924." Rainier Beach Dry Goods appears on the left side of the building.
subjects: Seattle Public Library. Rainier Beach Branch

properties.title: View south from 2nd Ave. and Spring St., ca. 1915
properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle. Streets. 2nd Ave., c. 1915. Looking south toward L. C. Smith building." Note on back of photograph: "c. 1915 NATIVE SONS AND DAUGHTERS OF SEATTLE Cosmopolitan to a degree, about the only class of citizens limited in numbers are those who have been born in Seattle. This is due to the fact of this city's rapid growth, her population of 330,00 consisting largely of people who have come here from other localities. Perhaps the most picturesque as well as pathetic of all Seattle's types are the real "Native Children," or Siwashes who crouch at the feet of the skyscrapers and offer their quaint Indian baskets, mats, bead work, and other curios to the passing throng of tourists."

properties.title: Crawford and Harrington's wharf, 1882
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Wharves. Crawford and Harrington's wharf. 1882. Copy of original photograph by Werner Lenggenhager." From the Pacific Coast Architecture Database: "Located just to the south of Yesler's Wharf, the Crawford and Harrington Company Wharf was a significant docking spot for cargo ships during the 19th century. The wharf's eastern half would now occupy filled land, crossing Alaskan Way to roughly the foot of the Alaskan Way Viaduct. At the pier's western end was a small shed belonging to the Talbot Coal Yard."
properties.intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. Washington St.

properties.title: Wedgewood homes near 3164 NE 81st St., 1953
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Houses. Wedgewood housing development. East 81st Street west of 35th Ave. N. E. Wood. Developed by Albert Balch. View towards the north. Photo by Werner Lenggenhager, 1953." Transcribed from back of photograph: "WEDGEWOOD SPECULATIVE RESIDENTIAL DEVELOPMENT [i.e. Development] 1953 West of 35th Avenue N. E. at East 81st Street Developer: Albert Balchen [i.e. Balch] In this neighborhood of two hundred homes, the consistently related designs coupled with the preservation of the beautyfull [i.e. beautiful] trees have produced a charming and harmonious development. The modest two and three bed-room homes are variations of the basic plan with a few other designs for special situations. Strange as it seems, few project developers have been willing to save the trees and natural growth abounding in Seattle. Shown is North side of street facing south. Built in the 40's."

properties.title: Main Street School, December 12, 1921
properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. Main Street School. 6th and Main. Built 1873 and called South school; name changed to Main Street school 1889; enlarged 1900; demolished 1921. Frame. Exterior. Front view. Last day of school. Pupils being marched to new school (Bailey Gatzert) Dec. 12, 1921." Transcribed from back of photograph: “THE LAST DAY OF THE (Main Street) SOUTH SCHOOL was on Dec. 12, 1921, when the classes and their teachers were marched to the newly erected Bailey Gatzert School.  The old Main Street building was later used by the Park Department for a department stable and was finally torn down in recent years.  The foto shows the last classes that entered the building.”

properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. South School (first) 6th and Main. Built 1873 and called South School; name changed to Main Street School 1889. Frame. Exterior. View from right side and back. Ca. 1875. Retouched from the original." Transcribed from back of photo: “This Rare Picture is a close-up photograph of the original South School on Main Street, which was then the stage road leading to Leschi Park (present) On Lake Washington.  Then the shoreline of the bay was less than a block away.  This picture is reproduced from a faded original, and required some retouching.”

properties.title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound. Railroad depot and machine shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889? Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”

properties.title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound. Railroad depot and machine shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889? Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”

properties.title: Classes of South School, opening day, September 2, 1889
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Classes of South School, opening day, Sept. 2, 1889. Identified on balcony: Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, Florence Stowell (Hubbart) teacher, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller." Transcribed from back of photograph: “It was a “gala” day - and justified this picture of school, pupils and teachers, as they prepared to enter the new SOUTH SCHOOL for the first classes at the opening of the Fall term on the first Monday of September in 1889.  This and the Central were the city's first brick schools.  On the balcony are Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, teacher Florence Stowell, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller, among others.  This picture through the courtesy of the late Florence Stowell Hubbart.”

properties.title: King County Courthouse, ca. 1882
properties.description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Buildings. King County Court House. First. 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way . Built 1860; acquired by Seattle 1891. Exterior. Frame. View of front from left side. Ca. 1882. Public school classes were held here from 1864 to 1868." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Public School classes were held in this, originally the “old” County Building, at Third and Jefferson, from 1864-1868, before the community had its first school structure.  Teachers during these years included Dillis B. Ward, Mrs. Wm. Hammond, Mrs. Emma Preston, Mrs. Mary A. Smith, and Miss Carrie Bacon." Building served as the King County Courthouse and then Seattle's first City Hall.  Located on 3rd Ave. between Yesler Way and Jefferson Street.

properties.title: Potlatch Festival Tyee reception, July 17, 1912
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Golden Potlatch. July 15-20. Reception of the Tyee. View 2." From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of hte North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes," their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

Backside and yard of Victorian style Apt. house erected in 1890. While front shows a closed facade with its wedding cake decorations, rising sun motives, ever present like a pattern in those early structures, the backside is while plain not without its interesting features. One common outside stairway is used by all and the individual sections now appearing separate units are connected with a little bridge with its flower boxes to add a homey touch while the yard itself is being kept neat and orderly. Werner Lenggenhager."

properties.title: Blasting the old court house cupola, January 14, 1931
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle, Wash.Three remarkable pictures taken here recently which when perused from left to right form a spectacular movette depicting the removal by blasting of one of Seattle's oldest landmarks, the cupola of the old court house. At the left the ancient structure is shown standing, a second before the wrecker touched off the charge. In the center the entire building is shown a fraction of a second after the 200 sticks of dynamite had been exploded. The pillars atop the cupola are shown flying outward as the understructure is crumbling to ruin. At the right the whole mass of masonry is shown falling in a cloud of dust. Two photographers set their camera in such a way as to catch the three bits of action. Each of the men used two cameras to create the above effect. Great care was exercised to set the charge in such a manner that all debris would fall within the four walls. This was accomplished by placing the dynamite in 36 holes bored in the pillars, between the basement and the first floor. R-1-1-31 ABE.FM"

properties.title: First Presbyterian Church at 3rd Ave. and Madison St., 1889
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "This photograph shows left to right: First Presbyterian Church, Third and Madison, Residence of Amos Miller, Residence of M.B.V. Stacey, First Methodist [Episcopal] Church, Third and Marion. The First Presbyterian Church, pictured here, was the first structure erected for the congregation, built in 1877, with the first services in the building held on the first Sunday of July of that year; Rev. Theodore Crown then minister. Church Moved in 1893 to 4th and Spring, and again in 1907 to the present site at Seventh and Spring. Amos Miller site now part of a combined business structure. Stacey home now stands on top of a one story brick block, being used for a French restaurant. This First Methodist Church building erected in 1887, was an outgrowth of the city's first church, known as the "Little White Church" built at 2nd and Columbia, in the early 50's. The property at Third and Marion was sold in 1907 and the congregation established-in a new church at 5th and Marion still in use."

properties.title: Stewart and Holmes Drug Company baseball team, ca. 1913
properties.description: From "The Druggists' Circular and Chemical Gazette," Volume 46, June 1902:" "The wholesale department of the Stewart & Holmes Drug Company, at Seattle, will close on Saturdays at noon during the summer. The employees of the company have a crack baseball team, and the half holiday will give them the opportunity to play." In 1901, a Commercial Baseball League formed in Seattle including employees from various Seattle businesses. Seattle Times, April 19, 1901:""The employees of a number of the leading business houses of the city have held a conference and announce that they will have a commercial baseball league this season. Teams have already been formed in several of the stores and are practicing daily after working hours. Last year there were several store teams and number of first-class games were played between them. A great difficulty was found, however in arranging dates satisfactory to both sides. For this reason several of the more interested players of last year have promoted the league for this year. Their respective employers have consented to allow them a Saturday afternoon occasionally for a game and a committee of the league is at work preparing a regular schedule. A general meeting of the young men will be called in the near future when officers of the associations for the various teams will be elected. The following business houses will be represented: Seattle Hardware Company, Louch, Augustine *Co., Schwabacher Hardware Co., Mitchell, Lewis & Staver, M. Seller & Co., and A. Hambach & Co. It is possible that several more houses will be represented in the league after the project is a little more matured."
subjects: Stewart and Holmes Drug Company (Seattle, Wash.)
Stewart and Holmes Drug Company (Baseball Team)

properties.title: View west from 4th Ave. and Yesler Way, ca. 1912
properties.description: The Frye Hotel (also known as Hotel Frye) appears on the left. It was constructed in 1911 and designed by the architects Charles H. Bebb and Louis L. Mendel. The project was funded by Seattle pioneer George F. Frye and his wife Louisa Frye (originally of the Denny family). The hotel was converted to low income housing in the 1970s. City Hall Park is on the right, followed by the Arctic Club Building (home to Hotel Seward and The Alaskan)" A banner for John F. Murphy, Prosecuting Attorney appears further down the hill. Murphy ran for Prosecuting Attorney in 1910.

properties.title: Seattle City Light Emergency Generating Plant, ca. 1911
properties.description: The plant, also known as the Hydro House or the Power House, opened in 1912. It served as an emergency power supply for the city should the Cedar Dam plant fail.

properties.description: From the Seattle Times March 1, 1907 article "Baseball Men Meet Tonight:" "Members of the Seattle Athletic Club who are interested in baseball will need in the club rooms tonight to consider the matter of putting a team in the field this year. Money has already been appropriated  by the directors to buy uniforms and equipment. It is proposed to arrange a schedule of games between the local club and Multnomah and Spokane Athletic Clubs; the University of Washington, the Seattle High School and probably some of the amateur teams in and around the city. The manager of the team will not go outside of the club membership for material. There are so many ball players who, while they are not professionals in the sense that they follow the game as an avocation, still they would have trouble qualifying as amateurs, so no chances will be taken on having men protested. Barry, of last year's football team, is a good ball player; Brown is another man with a good record; Fowler is a clever southpaw, and in fact there is a lot of material that has only to be tried out to give the club a winning aggregation."

properties.title: 3rd Ave. north from Yesler Way, ca. 1908
properties.description: Hotel Seward, which appears on the bottom left of the photo, opened at the same time as the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition in 1909. It served as the headquarters for members of the Arctic Club. The buildings past the Hotel Seward on the left are the Drexel Hotel, the Lyon Building (constructed in 1910), and the St. Charles Hotel and Apartments (constructed in 1911). The Coliseum Theater, opened in 1908, appears at the right. The name of the theater was changed to the Orpheum in the same year it opened and the building was demolished in 1911.

properties.description: The player pictured here is also pictured in the 1907 and 1908 Seattle High School Sealth yearbooks but is not identified by name. Seattle High School was the first opened in the city and originally operated on the 3rd floor of the Central School. As Seattle grew and more high schools opened, the name of the school was briefly changed to Washington High School before becoming Broadway in 1908. Known as the Tigers for their orange and black team colors, the Seattle High traveled throughout the United States, gaining national recognition. The 1907 team sent seven players on to play professionally.

properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Religion and Sanitation Clash in Seattle. Seattle, Wash. A member of "The Church in Israel" talking with R. Metz of the Seattle Sanitation and Health Department following Metz's demand that the body of Daniel Salwt, prophet of the Israel organization be removed from their church and taken to an undertaking establishment. The disciples had refused to have the body touched saying it would interfere with resurrection. The dispute ended when the churchmen allowed the body to be removed on condition that it would not be embalmed for a certain period and that they be allowed to watch over it. R-6-20-29. EHP."

properties.title: Green Lake Library Branch, 1906
properties.description: From Green Lake's "About the Branch" article on spl.org: "Library service in Green Lake dates back to 1905, when The Seattle Public Library opened a small, one-room structure on the east side of the lake, several blocks south of the present building. The structure was built on a wooden platform. A board sidewalk led from the street and the streetcar tracks to the library. In rainy weather, the tiny building was surrounded by mud and water and young boys begged the librarian for twine so they could fish over the railing."
subjects: Seattle Public Library. Green Lake Branch

properties.title: Waterfront from Marion St. to Union St., ca. 1868

properties.title: Temperance Hall on E. 72nd St., 1891
properties.description: HistoryLink article "Green Lake School" states: "As a temporary measure to meet the growing needs of the 1,000 residents living nearby, in 1901 the school district opened two annexes at Green Lake. The first, about which little is known, was located on the site of the John Marshall school and provided space for two classrooms. The other occupied the two-story I.O.G.T. Hall at today's (1999) NE 72nd Street and 5th Avenue NE, above Baskin & Robbins. This temperance hall was home for three class rooms of second through fifth grade children during the 1901-02 school year."
subjects: Independent Order of Good Templars. Grand Lodge of Washington. Lodge No. 1 (Seattle, Wash.)

properties.title: Woodland Court Apartments, ca. 1930
properties.description: A September 9, 1917 Seattle Times article celebrating the opening of the apartments stated: "Of a distinctive type of modern apartment building is Woodland Court at the southeast corner of North Fiftieth Street and Fremont Avenue, at the main or boulevard entrance to Woodland Park, just completed by the Goodwin Real Estate at a cost of more than $45,000. The building has many novel attractions and was designed by George W. Lawton, well-known Seattle architect. It contains eighteen apartments of four and five rooms each, many with built-in glass sunrooms, or sleeping porches. The building is of solid brick construction, three stories and basement, covering a plot of ground 150 feet by 200 feet."

properties.title: Intelligencer Office near 1st Ave. and Cherry St., ca. 1876
properties.description: Constructed by Henry Yesler in 1874, this building served as an office for the Seattle Intelligencer Newspaper (which would later evolve into the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.)  The annotation on the photo "Founded by Higgins & Maxwell" refers to Samuel L. Maxwell and David Higgins who were early owners of the paper. The annotation elect "Judge Ike Hall" likely refers to Isaac Hall who served as one of the city's first attorneys and was involved with several unsuccessful attempts at newpaper publishing.

properties.title: Works Progress Administration sign at Green Lake, March 12, 1937
properties.description: HistoryLink article "Green Lake cleanup and redesign begins in 1936" states: "In the winter of 1936, a major, WPA-funded clean-up of Seattle's Green Lake is undertaken. For decades, the lake has been subject to algae bloom and outbreaks of green scum and foul odor, and swimmers have gotten swimmer's itch. The massive project includes dredging the lake, building an island (Swan Island, or Duck Island) as a wildlife sanctuary, and building a water-aerating fountain in the middle of the lake. The fountain is never built, but other parts of the project are carried out."

Marion A. Zioncheck's suicide note, August 9, 1936
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Zioncheck's last written statement. Here is the suicide note left by Representative Marion A. Zioncheck, congressman from Seattle, before he leaped to his death from the 5th story of the Arctic Building in Seattle, August 7." The suicide note reads: "My only hope in life was to improve the condition of an unfair economic system that held no promise to those that all the wealth of even a decent chance to survive let alone live." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

properties.title: Marion A. Zioncheck being transported from Gallinger Hospital, June 23, 1936
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Rep. Zioncheck Moved. Rep. Marion Zioncheck, of Washington, angrily shouted that he was being mistreated, was carried out of Gallinger Hospital, in Washington, D.C., June 23, and hustled away in an ambulance to a private sanitarium in Baltimore. Zioncheck said the hospital authorities had him in a straightjacket, but this charge was denied by the hospital superintendent who said he was put in a "pack" because he resisted attendants when they were moving him. The "pac" - tight wrapping in sheets - has the same effect as a straightjacket. Photo shows - Rep. Zioncheck being removed from Gallinger Hospital." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

properties.title: Space Needle from south gate of the World's Fair, 1962
properties.description: South Entrance and Space Needle, Century 21 Exposition (Seattle World's Fair). On the South Entrance, designed by Bassetti & Morse: "Douglas fir logs turned on giant lathe by Cascade Pole Co. and painted rainbow of colors, greet visitors on south side."" (An Architect's Guidebook to the Seattle Worlds Fair. Seattle, Pacific Builder and Engineer, April 1962, p. 31). Space Needle: ""The Space Needle, a modernistic totem of the Seattle Worlds Fair, was conceived by Eddie Carlson as a doodle in 1959 and given form by architects John Graham Jr., Victor Steinbrueck, and John Ridley. When King County declined to fund the project, five private investors, Bagley Wright, Ned Skinner, Norton Clapp, John Graham Jr., and Howard S. Wright, took over and built the 605-foot tower in less than a year." (Walt Crowley, Space Needle (Seattle). HistoryLink.org, http://historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=1424)

properties.title: Interior of Marion A. Zioncheck's Washington D.C. apartment, May 26, 1936
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Hold for wire release from Mr. Dorman! These pictures show the condition of the apartment occupied by Re. Marion Zioncheck, in Washington D.C., as of May 21. Zioncheck was dispossessed by Mrs. Pamela Schuyler Young, who sub-leased the apartment to him. Negative 46 shows Zioncheck's famous Indian gear, heaped at one end of the room with other paraphernalia." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

properties.title: Flag Plaza, Armory and Space Needle, 1962
properties.description: Plaza of the States, Century 21 Exposition (Seattle Worlds Fair). "Created at the specific request of Washington's Governor Albert D. Rosellini and erected from funds voted by the Legislature, the Plaza of the States is a flag-surrounded open-air ceremonial area used for special programs honoring the fifty states. Located in the geographic center of the fairgrounds, the area contains a bandstand, speakers' platform and a huge, gas-fed flame font -- symbol of the unity of the states. The flame will burn throughout the 184 days of the Fair." (Official press book: Seattle World's Fair 1962. Seattle: Century 21 Exposition, 1962, p. 65.)
subjects: Plaza of the States (Century 21 Exposition, 1962, Seattle, Wash.)

properties.title: Canada Pavilion and fountain, 1962
properties.description: Canada Pavilion of the Century 21 Exposition (Seattle World's Fair). "Surrounding the Coliseum is 94,200 sq. ft. of exhibit space in clear span structures of concrete columns and tilt-up walls with a steel joist roof system and metal decking and insulation. The concrete, laid out in a repetitive form which has become the architect's trademark, relieves what might otherwise have become a monotonous perimeter facade." (An Architect's Guidebook to the Seattle World's Fair. Seattle, Pacific Builder and Engineer, April 1962, p. 19)

properties.title: Barney Ross, national welter weight, meeting with Howard Dent Jr. from University of Washington, April 2, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1508. Barney Ross arrives in Seattle for match with Henry Wood for title. Seattle, Washington. - Barney Ross, National welter weight has arrived in Seattle to defend his title against Henry Wood, the sturdy Washingtonian in a twelve round bout in Seattle's civic auditorium next week. The champion looks good after a few weeks in the hot springs and there is little doubt that he will come out the heavy man on the tales to put Woods away in a hurry. The first man to greet Ross at the Seattle[Washington] Athletic Club Training quarters was Howard Dent, jr. heavy weight wrestler of the University of Washington. Dent is the blind wrestler who has astonished the world wi th his blind skill in the heavies. His weight is 190 pounds and he is just now slated to take on a bout at Multnomah Club of Portland in the P.N.A. of the A.A.U. wrestling tournament. Photo shows Barney Ross wishing good luck to the blind wrestler on his tour of the Northwest. Direct service...4/2/35...exclusive."

properties.title: Bertha Barkhoff and Zoe Smith, badminton finalists, April 1, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1507. Badminton stars come through according to form. Mrs. Bert Barkhoff [Bertha] and Zoe Smith of Seattle won their place in the State finals at Badminton at Queen Anne Hall last night. After a tour of the Pacific Coast this team came right back and showed the homefolk that their awards were of the first water. They won their set be a score of 15-11 to 15-8. Photo shows Mrs. Barkhoff shooting a back-hand with Miss Zoe Smith backing up. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Collapsed East Gate at World Fair grounds, February 26, 1962
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Builders' Work is Un-Fair. What goes up must come down. But workmen erecting the facilities for the Seattle World's Fair are not pleased that their work is undone before the exposition opens. A 40-foot-high laminated wooden arch at the main east entryway collapsed into a heap of splinters Monday. Construction foreman Del Yount said he thought a gust of wind did the damage. The Men were standing under the arch but escaped without injury."

properties.title: 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. after the fire, July 1889
Paul Satko's children being taken into custody by Juvenile Court, April 25, 1940
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "562778. Children taken from Alaska-bound ark. Seattle--Despite efforts to hid in the hold of the home-made Ark of Juneau, bound from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska, five of the minor children of Paul Satko were taken into temporary custody by the Juvenile Court at Seattle. The action came after a court order was served on Satko, ordering him to turn the children over to authorties on grounds that the ark was unsafe. Here the children are shown on their way to court. Hazel, 18, who wasn't held; Joe, 16; David, 9; Billie, 8; and Grace, 11, partly hidden. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

properties.title: Cherry St. in the snow, January 10, 1880
properties.description: Seattle in snow. Cherry Street looking northeast. Store signs: Coulter & Shillestad Undertakers, Spring-Beds.

properties.title: Shirley Frazier, March 13, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1459. Shirley Frazer is best riflewoman in U.S. Seattle, Washington. - 100, 100 100, 99, 99, 100 is the way the scorer chalked up this Co-ed's record in the National shoot. Miss Frazer is a University of Washington co-ed and in her recent record she got 598 out of a possible 600, which is only one point removed from an all time record, she tied last year with Mary Wettach of Carnegie Tech and lost the toss of the coin for first place. Direct service...3/13/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Hilde McAuslan, Washington State champion golfer, August 19, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1110. Young Seattle star retains golf crown. Seattle, Washington.- Hilde McAuslan, brilliant young Seattle golfer went through the Washington State Championship contest in nearly far [sic] form to retain her hold on the state title, beating her final rival 14 up and 12 to go. Photo shows Seattle's own Hilda the perfect stylist. Direct service...8/20/34. Exclusive..." Seattle Times articles from August 19 state that the championship took place at the Broadmoor Golf Course.

properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA 1162. Left wing of the Huskies. Seattle, Washington. - Five hundred and seventy seven pound of University of Washington left wing is a powerful aggregation. Chuck Mucha 191 guard from Chicago, Woody Ullin, 192 lbs tackel from Centralia, Washington captain and Dan Lazaravich 194 lb end from Chicago. Direct service...9/18/34..."

Seattle from Elliott Bay, ca. 1930
properties.description: The Northern Life Tower can be seen at the left of the photograph. Smith Tower and the Colman Dock appear at the right.

properties.title: Badminton players Keith Weston and Hamilton Law, January 28, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1382. Favorites come through badminton tourney. Seattle, Washington. - The biggest entry list in the state has just finished a week of badminton tournament. With players from all parts of the country, Seattle stars won their way through the finals. Photo shows winners in the men's doubles Keith Weston and Hamilton Law on the courts of Queen Anne Hall. Law also one shuttle contest. Direct service... 1/28/35...exclusive..." The 1935 city directory lists Queen Anne Hall at 713 1st Ave. W.

properties.title: Cornish dance students in Volunteer Park, April 19, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1552. Its springtime in Seattle. Seattle Washington. - The farthest north big metropolis in United States is putting on her fine garments for Easter and with all the spring beauty, comes the fait maiden to dance with joy for the spring. Out in Volunteer Park, on top of the highest knowl [sic] in the city, blossoms are at their best, even calling Cornish School dancers to romp in the warm sunshine and fragrance of the season atmosphere. Photo shows Doreen Lang, of San Francisco, Eve Simeon Seattle and Nina Fonaroff of New York City in their Albanian costumes folk dance in Volunteer Park. Direct service...4/19/1935...exclusive..."
subjects: Cornish School of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)

properties.title: President Garfield Memorial Service at Occidental Hotel, September 26, 1881
Lake Washington Blvd. looking toward Mt. Rainier, ca. 1910
Aurora Kippenberg and Helene Madison at the Alki Marathon, July 29, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1049. Aurora Kippenberg, heroine of Alki Marathon. Seattle, Washington. - Three girls and one man finish the Hi-Yu marathon, that is one of the greatest tests in this part of the country. There were 35 entries, but physical tests forbade all but fifteen in taking the change. Among these where was one man and three girls. Photo shows Miss Aurora Kippenberg being given the grease treatment by Helene Madison Seattle's wonder girl swimmer. Direct service...7/29/34..."

properties.title: Washington Athletic Club relay team and coach, March 13, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1485. Coach Daughters gives relay last workout before coming to eastern meet. Seattle, Washington. - Coach Ray Daughters gave his wonder girl relay team a fast workout and instructions before he started for an eastern invasion in swimming meets. His relay team will take daily workouts and join their coach in Chicago on April 4th to compete in the women's national indoor meet at Lakeshore. A.C. L to R: Mary Lou Petty, Olive McKean, Betty Lee, Doris Buckley, and Coach Ray Daughters.  Direct service...3/22/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Seattle Mayor Charles L. Smith, ca., 1935
properties.description: Smith served as Mayor between 1934 and 1936.

properties.title: World's Fair visitors at post office, 1962
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle -- World's Fair visitors head for the Space Needle Station of the Seattle Post Office. The Post Office is next to the Great Britain Exhibit. (World's Fair Photo No. PO 6697mf)."
subjects: United States Post Office (Century 21 Exposition, 1962, Seattle, Wash.)

properties.title: Crowd cheering returning troops, March 3, 1952
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle-style welcome: Despite the fact that it was Sunday-and a chilly afternoon, hundreds of Seattleites assembled at Third Avenue "Welcome Lane" yesterday to cheer troops who arrived from the Far East aboard the transport Antolak. The ceremony was held between Union and Pike Streets. The convoy of busses took the troops to Fort Lawton. Mar. 3, 1952." Photograph appeared in the Seattle Times.

properties.title: Satko family on grounded "Ark" in Seattle, April 30, 1940
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "NY 162--Paul Satko, Richmond welder, his wife and 7 children study plight after ark they started to Alaska on went aground off Seattle."

properties.title: Pioneer Building, ca. 1910
properties.description: The Pioneer Building appears in the center of the photograph with the Howard Building to its left and Hotel Seattle to its right.

properties.title: Paul Satko being served with court order, April 26, 1940
properties.description: Seattle Times, April 27, 1940: Transcribed from photograph: "553779. Owner of Alaska-Bound Ark jailed. Seattle--Paul Satko's pioneering journey from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska in his homemade Ark of Juneau was interrupted when he was arrested for resisting an officer and five of his seven children were taken into temporary custody of the juvenile court at Seattle. His arrest came after he was served with a court order to turn the children over to authorities on grounds that the ark was unsafe. The previous day the ark had cone aground in Puget Sound. This picture shows the order being served. Satko is in the center wearing overalls. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40."

properties.title: Henry L. Yesler residence, ca. 1890
properties.description: After Henry Yesler's death, the mansion housed the Seattle Public Library. It was destroyed in a 1901 fire.

properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA 1180: Look what Art Ahonen brought back from Ironwood Michigan. Seattle, Washington. - Art Ahonen big end of University of Washington for the third year has just reported to coach Phelan. The boss needed a center and art brought one for him, all the way form Ironwood, Michigan. He is Tom Yelich at the left in this photograph. Art is telling him to look like Ironwood. Direct service...9/24/34..."

properties.title: View north on 2nd Ave. from Yesler Way, ca. 1923
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "The downtown business section, Seattle. Looking north up 2nd Ave, with Elliott Bay and the Olympic Mountains to the west." Photo is likely taken from Smith Tower. The Mehlhorn and Empire buildings appear on the right.

properties.title: University of Washington Shipping Board School, 1918
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "U.S. Shipping Board School. U of W. 1918." The Shipping Board School was a free program in Marine Engineering established at the University of Washington by the United States Shipping Board.

properties.title: Yesler home near 1st Ave. and Yesler Way, 1860
properties.description: The same photograph is appears in the Prosch Seattle Views Collection at the University of Washington with the following description: "This is the oldest or first known photograph of any part of Seattle. It represents that part of town from the south line of Cherry Street on the left to the north line of James Street on the right, extending from First to Third Avenues east and west. The buildings shown are the Yesler dwelling in the foreground, and two barns or outbuildings of his. The Hillory Butler Home is back of Yesler's. Opposite the nearest barn is the L.V. Wyckoff house. On its right is the H.A. Smith house. South of James St. is the S.D. Libby house, later that of John Collins. These buildings occupied the ground now covered by immense brick houses, reaching up to sixteen stories in one case. The pole shown stood in front of the Yesler sawmill, where Pioneer Place now is. A V-shaped flume shows in the picture. It brought water down James Street. Seattle's first shade trees, framed in, are seen, or supposed to be seen on the right of the Yesler house. The picture was taken in 1860."

properties.title: Seattle Seahawks hockey team, March 25, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1492: It looks like Seahawks for Championship for Northwest League."" March 25, 1935. Seattle, Washington.- 4,000 hockey fans rattled the rafters of Seattle Ice Arena in a crucial game of the 35 season playoff on Sunday. As it stands the Seattle team has two to one advantage over the Vancouver team and if Seahawks win the next it will be all over. The next game is to be played in Vancouver and if necessary for the fifth game it will be played in Seattle this weekend. L to R. Couch and Manager Frank Foyston, Johnny Houbregs, Moon Mullen, defense, Cameron Proudlock forward, Tony Hemerling, forward, Harold Tabor, forward, Les Whittles, forward, Dave Gilhooly defense and Emmett Venne goalie. Seattle 5, Vancouver 2. Direct service...3/35/35..."

properties.title: Boxing match between Barney Ross and Henry Wood, April 10, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1528. Barney Ross wins decision over Henry Wood in 12 round battle. Seattle, Washington. - When Henry Wood ran into a haymaker. Photo shows left Henry Wood welter weight running into one of Barney Ross's left hooks to the face. New York and Chicago. 4/10/35." According to Seattle Times articles from April 10, the match took place in the Civic Auditorium.

properties.title: Civic Auditorium and Mount Rainier, ca. 1950
properties.description: Photograph taken looking south from lower Queen Anne. The Civic Auditorium and Armory appear on the lower right and Mount Rainier appears in the center.

properties.title: Fire at Brace Lumber Company, May 10, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1588. Strike pickets blamed for hampering firemen at Seattle midnight fire. Seattle, Washington. - With the lumber industry tied up on account labor troubles, it is believed that the $15,000 fire that swept the Brace Lumber Company in ruins and threatened destruction to a big brewery and an oil and gas storage company in the same block, that striking pickets did hamper the work of the fire department of Seattle last night at midnight. Photo shows the raging fire within a few feet of the big brewery. Direct service...5/10/1935..." The 1935 city directory lists the Brace Lumber Company at 925 Valley St.

properties.title: Harry Givan plays for a place in the National Open, May 14, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1612. Northwest all set for two siege guns for National Open. Seattle, Washington. - Harry Givan, ""Amateur"" of Seattle shot a 142 for an [illegible] test to place in the National Open in Pittsburgh June 6,7, and 8th. His 142 was four strokes above par for the 36 holes. Direct service...5/15/35...exclusive..." A May 14, 1935 Seattle Times article identifies the location of the competition at the Seattle Golf Club.

properties.title: View SE from 4th Ave. and Seneca St., 1887
properties.description: Providence Hospital appears in the center of the photograph and the Central School appears above it to the left.

properties.title: Waterfront between Madison and Columbia St., 1887
properties.description: Seattle waterfront between Columbia and Madison Street. YMCA, Budlong's boathouse, and Golden Rule Bazaar.

properties.title: Queen Coffee and Waffle House interior, ca. 1910
properties.description: A 1910 Seattle Times article lists the Waffle House at 119 1/2 W. Main St. This refers to the area west of 1st Ave. that is now called S. Main St. The 119 location corresponds roughly with the present day address of 81 S. Main St.
subjects: Queen Coffee and Waffle House (Seattle, Wash.)

properties.title: Paul and Hazel Satko with lawyers, April 27, 1940
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Friends come to aid of Paul Satko, unemployed welder, at Seattle April 25, after his Alaska trip in a home-made Ark was halted by legal complaints the craft was unsafe. He's shown here conferring outside juvenile court, which took custody of his children. Left to right, Lee Merrill, Tacoma, Wash., supporter; Hazel Satko, 18; Satko; and attorneys Horace Geer and Milton Heiman." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

properties.title: Baron Walter von Pachman of Bavaria, February 27, 1929
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SF Bureau--Cleve--NY ACME--Airmail--Feb 27, 1929. He was Baron Walter von Pachman of Bavaria, son of a high German army officer and himself somewhat scarred in university duels. Now, he's a bus boy at Seattle Hotel, and his wife is a waitress in the coffee shop of the same hostelry. The pair are out of employment after the subdivision of a large ranch where he was agricultural expert, and between carrying trays, the Baron is looking for employment as a chemist."

properties.title: Tod Markow, UW football player, September 24, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA. 1179. Whats the mystery about Huskies? Seattle, Washington. - People don't think much of the Washington Huskies changes this year. "Too many graduates last spring" Coach Jimmie Phelan, but every time you size up a likely candidate and ask where he comes from. O! That guy comes from Chicago, or Michigan, or somewhere other than Washington where they raise tall timber. Tod Markow the tall end this year comes from Chicago and if Jimmie does not keep him under a blanket the early part of the season, he is just likely enough to start something. Direct service...9/24/34...exclusive..."

properties.title: Bob Swisher practicing high jump, March 22, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Husky jumpers trying out artificial lighting of indoors prepatory [sic] to Stanford meet. Seattle, Washington. - Bob Swisher, crack high jumper of the Washington Huskies is expected to give Stanford a hard run for first place in their meet at University of Washington Pavilion March 29 when the two teams meet for the first competitive event of the season for the Huskies. Heck Edmondson is still trying out his jumpers by strong lighting floods for the big event. Direct service...3/22/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Roosevelt Theater, 1953
properties.description: The Roosevelt Theater was first opened in 1933. The name of theater was changed to the Town Theater in 1964.

properties.title: Elsie Morrison, UW archer, December 24, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1#27. Archery Becoming Popular at University of Washington. Seattle, Washington. - Miss Elsie Morrison of the University of Washington shows how the co-eds keep fit these winter days when one cannot enjoy outdoor sports. It takes considerable strength to pull the big bow and developes the whole upper structure of the body. There are 24 different kinds of sports taught in the physical education department of U of Washington. Direct and section #3...12/24/34..."

properties.title: Mayor Edwin A. Brown and bull, February 11, 1926
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "20770. You may think this is a lot of bull. A real, honest-to-goodness bull strolled into the office of Mayor Edwin Brown, of Seattle, Wash., the other day. The mayor granted the bull the privilege of an executive conference, but refused to divulge the details."

properties.title: George Eddy, inventor of the golf fairway vacuum cleaner, November 16, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1266. Three cheers for inventor of golf fairway vacuum cleaner. Seattle, Washington. - George Eddy, owner of Foster Golf Course, has solved the question of the Autumn, when the leaves are falling and you know that your ball is straight down the fairway, but still cannot find it on account of leaves on the course. "Well just call George and he will do it." Edwards has invented a vacuum cleaner for the golf links and it works, no matter what the conditions, George will guarantee a clean course. The cleaner is not unlike then ordinary household vacuum cleaner, in principal, but hitched to a tractor it runs over the course and takes every fallen leaf. Direct service...11/16/34...exclusive..."

properties.title: View east from 4th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St., June 1920
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Book page 224. Historic railway terminal (at right). Seattle, Wash. Photo by H.H. Waller. June 1920." Union Station appears to the right. Hotel Idaho is visible in the center of the photograph.

properties.title: A.J. Heller and Earl Martin outside of Labor Temple, July 16, 1919
Bertha Barkhoff, badminton champion, April 1, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1506. Seattle, Washington. - Mrs. Bert [Bertha] Barkhoff took a few lessons recently from the great National Champion, Jess Willard, and then went right out and beat the best they had to offer in Portland, Oregon, then to San Francisco she won the women's championship and on the Los Angeles she still was the best in the singles and now she is back on her home courts and last night she captured the singles and paired with Miss Zoe Smith took the women's doubles. Photo shows Mrs. Bert Barkhoff with one of her easy back-hand sweeps that is deadly to her opponent. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Bob Snyder of Butterfly Bob's Salad Bar, October 8, 1974
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "ARP 092703--UNIPIX. Winged Delivery. Seattle, Wash: - Bob Snyder, co-owner of Butterfly Bob's Salad Bar here, hopes this outfit will attract attention to his business -- especially when he begins delivery service in the downtown area shortly. Bob says his wings will have big pockets to carry sandwiches, and he promises delivery with a half-hour of the order within a two-block radius of his restaurant. Credit (UPI). 10/8/74."

properties.title: University of Washington vs. Idaho football game, September 19, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1185. Washington Huskies beat Idaho 13 to 0. Seattle, Washington. - Burl Bufkin nailed by of [sic] Idaho in an attempt to run the end was a clever bit of tackling for the Vandals. The Vandals held the Huskies for the first half and it was in the third quarter that Phelans mob got going. Direct service...9/29/34..."

The picture was taken in 1860."

properties.title: Seattle Seahawks hockey team, March 25, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1492: It looks like Seahawks for Championship for Northwest League."" March 25, 1935. Seattle, Washington.- 4,000 hockey fans rattled the rafters of Seattle Ice Arena in a crucial game of the 35 season playoff on Sunday. As it stands the Seattle team has two to one advantage over the Vancouver team and if Seahawks win the next it will be all over. The next game is to be played in Vancouver and if necessary for the fifth game it will be played in Seattle this weekend. L to R. Couch and Manager Frank Foyston, Johnny Houbregs, Moon Mullen, defense, Cameron Proudlock forward, Tony Hemerling, forward, Harold Tabor, forward, Les Whittles, forward, Dave Gilhooly defense and Emmett Venne goalie. Seattle 5, Vancouver 2. Direct service...3/35/35..."

properties.title: Barney Ross, national welter weight, meeting with Howard Dent Jr. from University of Washington, April 2, 1935
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1508. Barney Ross arrives in Seattle for match with Henry Wood for title. Seattle, Washington. - Barney Ross, National welter weight has arrived in Seattle to defend his title against Henry Wood, the sturdy Washingtonian in a twelve round bout in Seattle's civic auditorium next week. The champion looks good after a few weeks in the hot springs and there is little doubt that he will come out the heavy man on the tales to put Woods away in a hurry. The first man to greet Ross at the Seattle[Washington] Athletic Club Training quarters was Howard Dent, jr. heavy weight wrestler of the University of Washington. Dent is the blind wrestler who has astonished the world wi th his blind skill in the heavies. His weight is 190 pounds and he is just now slated to take on a bout at Multnomah Club of Portland in the P.N.A. of the A.A.U. wrestling tournament. Photo shows Barney Ross wishing good luck to the blind wrestler on his tour of the Northwest. Direct service...4/2/35...exclusive."

After a tour of the Pacific Coast this team came right back and showed the homefolk that their awards were of the first water. They won their set be a score of 15-11 to 15-8. Photo shows Mrs. Barkhoff shooting a back-hand with Miss Zoe Smith backing up. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

properties.title: Collapsed East Gate at World Fair grounds, February 26, 1962
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Builders' Work is Un-Fair. What goes up must come down. But workmen erecting the facilities for the Seattle World's Fair are not pleased that their work is undone before the exposition opens. A 40-foot-high laminated wooden arch at the main east entryway collapsed into a heap of splinters Monday. Construction foreman Del Yount said he thought a gust of wind did the damage. The Men were standing under the arch but escaped without injury."

properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "562778. Children taken from Alaska-bound ark. Seattle--Despite efforts to hid in the hold of the home-made Ark of Juneau, bound from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska, five of the minor children of Paul Satko were taken into temporary custody by the Juvenile Court at Seattle. The action came after a court order was served on Satko, ordering him to turn the children over to authorties on grounds that the ark was unsafe. Here the children are shown on their way to court. Hazel, 18, who wasn't held; Joe, 16; David, 9; Billie, 8; and Grace, 11, partly hidden. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

It's not necessary to wear a bathing suit at all. Mrs. Frank Curtis obliged and the photographer used good judgement. The other lady is Mrs. Hazel McCraig wife of the inventor, she's not afraid, you will attest riding in her slacks. It's lots of fun riding the swells from the big steamers. properties.title: Igorrote Village at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
properties.description: From the Official guide to the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition: "Commandingly located at the head of the South Pay Streak, beneath of a roof of trees, is the picturesquely simple village of the barbaric Igorrotes, the interesting primitive and wild people from the remote mountain fastnesses of Luzon in the Philippine Archipelago. Here, in the greatest of all the special attractions, there are fifty of these strange head-hunting, dog-eating people, living as they live at home, in quint grass-thatched huts, with their womenkind and cute little children. A bit of their own characteristic Bontoc country transplanted in Seattle to show exposition visitors the manners, customs, costumes, industries, sports and pastimes of a remarkable people in the childhood of a race, a wild, uncultured people, struggling to break through their environment and emerge from the superstitions which enslave them, and to solve the mysterious play of the forces of nature and rise to higher conceptions of truth of freedom and liberty. Within the great palisaded enclosure there is not one inch of space that does not vibrate with the wild life of the Igorrotes. Everything they make and use at home is made in the Village here, men fashioning keen spears and warlike head axes at a primitive forge, or weaving rattan into peculiar pocket hats which distinguish the Bontoc men from all other Islanders; men carving war shields with crude tools, and quiet turbaned men from Sebangan molding clay and brass pipes and ornamental metal chains. Women spinning and weaving cotton into the gaudy "gee-strings" worn by the warriors, as well as the gay cloths for their own simple but sufficient clothing; others beating and winnowing rice, and many of both sexes laboring in the remarkable "sementeras" which terrace the mountainside at the rear of the Village, where rice is grown under irrigation as practiced by them at home. All in all, it is the most extensive, interesting and amusing exhibit at the exposition."

properties.title: Hoo-Hoo House at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
properties.description: From the Official guide to the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition: "The Hoo Hoo house on the grounds of the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition is a building of the bungalow type and is a haven of rest for all lumbermen who visit the fair. The building is so designed and large enough for association meetings, Hoo Hoo gatherings, concatenations, banquets, dancing parties and receptions. There is a large assemble room, checkrooms and an information bureau, where visiting lumbermen may register and be directed to hotels. Lumbermen will also have the privilege of having their mail addressed in care of the building. One of the special features of the Hoo Hoo building is the ladies reception and waiting rooms where Japanese maids in native costume are in attendance during the progress of the fair. There is also an attractive smoking room for men. The Hoo Hoo building is located near the Forestry building, the larges log house ever built. The funds to construct this building were secured from members of the order. The membership fee was placed at $9.99 and members for the exposition Hoo Hoo building are scattered all over the western states. The Hoo Hoo building is one of the most attractive of the smaller structures on the grounds of the 1909 exhibition. The Hoo Hoo , as everyone knows, is an organization of lumbermen, and since the lumber industry is the largest in the Northwest, thousands of lumbermen, lumber dealers, railroad men, sawmill machinery and supply men, as well as lumber journalists, will no doubt be in Seattle while the fair is open, and the Hoo Hoo building will be their headquarters. The structure was finished and furnished before the exposition opened.""

Forestry Building at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
properties.description: From the Official guide to the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition: "The Forestry building at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition is one of the most striking structures on the grounds and is a city block in length. At the close of the exposition this building will revert to the University and Washington's seat of learning will be the only educational institution in the world having a building of that character for use of students taking the forestry course. The Forestry building is one of the largest log houses ever built."" The building has a frontage of 320 feet and in width is 144 feet. About the front of the building are 124 logs, each forty feet high, containing 6,000 feet in board measure. The weight of each log is estimated at 50,000 pounds. The logs used on the exterior of the building are left in the rough, while those used in the interior have the bark removed. At each end of the building is a tower built of small logs, reached by a spiral stairway. The building has a balcony for exhibition purposes. The Forestry building is entirely complete and all exhibits were in place thirty days before the exposition opened. The exhibit in the Forestry building is complete in every detail. There is a comprehensive display of timber of various kinds showing the logs just as they leave the forest, besides sections and cross-sections of the big timbers. The various kinds of woods in a finished condition are also displayed and there are many samples showing flooring, paneling, ceiling work and other uses to which wood is put to decorate the interior of residence and office buildings. In connection with the forestry exhibit at the exposition is the timber testing plant located in the machinery hall adjoining the Forestry building. During the progress of the exposition timbers of every kind and all sizes will be tested to the breaking point. this is one of the most instructive demonstrations of the exposition, and is of interest to builders from every part of the country who attend the Seattle exposition."

Igorrote Village at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
properties.description: From the Official guide to the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition: "Commandingly located at the head of the South Pay Streak, beneath of a roof of trees, is the picturesquely simple village of the barbaric Igorrotes, the interesting primitive and wild people from the remote mountain fastnesses of Luzon in the Philippine Archipelago. Here, in the greatest of all the special attractions, there are fifty of these strange head-hunting, dog-eating people, living as they live at home, in quint grass-thatched huts, with their womenkind and cute little children. A bit of their own characteristic Bontoc country transplanted in Seattle to show exposition visitors the manners, customs, costumes, industries, sports and pastimes of a remarkable people in the childhood of a race, a wild, uncultured people, struggling to break through their environment and emerge from the superstitions which enslave them, and to solve the mysterious play of the forces of nature and rise to higher conceptions of truth of freedom and liberty. Within the great palisaded enclosure there is not one inch of space that does not vibrate with the wild life of the Igorrotes. Everything they make and use at home is made in the Village here, men fashioning keen spears and warlike head axes at a primitive forge, or weaving rattan into peculiar pocket hats which distinguish the Bontoc men from all other Islanders; men carving war shields with crude tools, and quiet turbaned men from Sebangan molding clay and brass pipes and ornamental metal chains. Women spinning and weaving cotton into the gaudy "gee-strings" worn by the warriors, as well as the gay cloths for their own simple but sufficient clothing; others beating and winnowing rice, and many of both sexes laboring in the remarkable "sementeras" which terrace the mountainside at the rear of the Village, where rice is grown under irrigation as practiced by them at home. All in all, it is the most extensive, interesting and amusing exhibit at the exposition."

properties.title: Providence Hospital, ca. 1889
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: ""Providence Hospital was established in Seattle 1877 by the Sisters of Charity, first established under contract in the old county hospital, or building which passed as such, located on the Duwamish river in what later became Georgetown. In 1878 they bought the block at 5th and Madison on which the building shown in this foot was erected. The first section built is shown as being the little left-hand corner. Next came the center section in 1882 and a few years later the first section, completing the structure as shown. This foot was evidently taken in 1889 or 1890, before the Madison Street cable line was placed in operation in 1890. The last and present Providence Hospital, at 17th and Jefferson Street, was built in 1911 and the old property sold. In recent years the government took over this original hospital block and now have erected a magnificent Federal Court house building on the site.""

properties.title: King Street Station, 1907
properties.description: During the early 1900s, there was increasing interest in connecting railroads with Seattle. The high demand and competition between railways resulted in two railway stations being built directly next to each other at 4th Avenue and Jackson Street. King Street Station (which is depicted here) was constructed in 1906 and can be distinguished by its tower. Union Station, originally known as the Oregon and Washington Station, was constructed in 1911. (Alternative names for Union Station include the Union Depot and the Northern Pacific Great Northern Depot.) Both stations were sometimes referred to as ""union stations"" or ""union depots"" due to the fact that multiple railroad lines were shared within the same terminal.

Morris D. Tacher, restaurant owner, December 4, 1949
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "[Photo caption] Specialties simmer in their exotic sauces on the stove at Morris Tacher's restaurant. Seasoning is a vital part of Tacher's cooking and meals present many unusual vegetables and other foods. [Obituary] Morris D. Tacher, 78, of 4726 50th Av. S., Seattle restaurant owner and operator 29 years, died today of cancer in a hospital. Born in Celevria, Turkey, Mr. Tacher came to Seattle from there in 1913. He owned, and, until his illness, operated the Turkish Restaurant in the Pike Place Market. Mr. Tacher was a retired member of Local 104, Boilermaker's Union; a member of the Seattle Sephardic Brotherhood and Sephardic Bikur Cholim Synagogue. Surviving are his wife, Selda, three sons, David and Jack Tacher, both of Seattle, and Sol Tacher, Bellevue; two daughters, Mrs. Ay Oziel, Seattle, and Mrs. Mike Cordova, Bellevue, and 18 grandchildren. Funeral services will be at 1 o'clock tomorrow at the Seattle Jewish Chapel, with burial in Bikur Cholim. The family suggests remembrances to the Cancer Fund." The photograph appeared in a Seattle Times article on Tacher on December 4, 1949. Tacher passed away July 8, 1965. According to the 1948/1949 City Directory, the restaurant was located at 87 Pike St., stall 9.

The bus, shown here after being towed to higher ground, collided with an oil truck and plunged into the Duwamish River carrying 19 Seattle-bound passengers. Photo courtesy Washington State Patrol by E.W. Kenyon, Jr. 64. Credit Line (ACME Photo)." The April 8, 1946 Seattle Times article ""Stage Careens into Duwamish after Collision"" notes that the location of the accident was near the Pacific Highway (now referred to as Highway 99) and S. 104th St.
properties.photographer: Washington State PatrolKenyon, E.W., Jr.Acme Newspictures

properties.title: Model airplane contest, August 1914
properties.description: According to the library's 1914 annual report: "In August the library conducted an aeroplane contest managed by Miss Hunter, children's librarian of the University branch. The original plan was for a contest among the boys of the University District only, but the interest was so widespread that it was finally opened to all the boys in the city. With the help of Mr. Howard Stine, playground director of the Park Department, and the playground instructors, the field arrangements were made and two contests were held a week apart. Prizes were donated by various interested people of the city and much newspaper publicity was secured. One of the large department stores displayed the prices in its window together with some of the models entered. , and moving pictures of the meet were shown at a local theater the following week. The books on model aeroplanes are in constant circulation and there is great interest in the possibility of another contest in 1915. Many boys who formerly regarded the library as a place to prepare lessons, now look upon it as a source of information on subjects in which they are keenly interested." An August 27, 1914 Seattle Star article lists the location of the meet at the Optimo Playfield at 29th Ave. and E. Cherry St. An August 20, 1914 article in the Seattle Times which announced the rules for the competition refers to the field as Optimo Grounds.

properties.title: Seattle Public Library booth at Child Welfare Exhibit, May 25-31, 1914
properties.description: According to the 1914 annual report: "The Library's share in the Child Welfare Exhibit, held at the Armory the last week in May, consisted of space twelve by thirty feet in which a miniature children's room was installed, with low tables, chairs, pictures, and flowering plants. About 600 books purchased for the Yesler Branch, which opened in September, were shelved in the library enclosure and these were circulated to children holding library cards. At one end of the space were seven screens telling of library activities by means of photographs and posters. Special shelves were reserved for books recommended for a child's own library, a collection of undesirable books for children, and a list of books for mothers concerning care of children. A list of books for a child's own library was distributed and a pamphlet called "Library babies are better babies" was given out. Attendants were always in charge to explain the work of the library to visitors, and the grown people were so interested that at times the children were crowded out." The Armory Building that housed the exhibit stood from 1909 to 1968 in the location now occupied by Victor Steinbrueck Park.

properties.title: Seattle Public Library booth at Child Welfare Exhibit, May 25-31, 1914
properties.description: According to the 1914 annual report: "The Library's share in the Child Welfare Exhibit, held at the Armory the last week in May, consisted of space twelve by thirty feet in which a miniature children's room was installed, with low tables, chairs, pictures, and flowering plants. About 600 books purchased for the Yesler Branch, which opened in September, were shelved in the library enclosure and these were circulated to children holding library cards. At one end of the space were seven screens telling of library activities by means of photographs and posters. Special shelves were reserved for books recommended for a child's own library, a collection of undesirable books for children, and a list of books for mothers concerning care of children. A list of books for a child's own library was distributed and a pamphlet called "Library babies are better babies" was given out. Attendants were always in charge to explain the work of the library to visitors, and the grown people were so interested that at times the children were crowded out." The Armory Building that housed the exhibit stood from 1909 to 1968 in the location now occupied by Victor Steinbrueck Park.

properties.title: Igorrotes at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition, 1909
properties.description: From the Official guide to the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition: "Commandingly located at the head of the South Pay Streak, beneath of a roof of trees, is the picturesquely simple village of the barbaric Igorrotes, the interesting primitive and wild people from the remote mountain fastnesses of Luzon in the Philippine Archipelago. Here, in the greatest of all the special attractions, there are fifty of these strange head-hunting, dog-eating people, living as they live at home, in quint grass-thatched huts, with their womenkind and cute little children. A bit of their own characteristic Bontoc country transplanted in Seattle to show exposition visitors the manners, customs, costumes, industries, sports and pastimes of a remarkable people in the childhood of a race, a wild, uncultured people, struggling to break through their environment and emerge from the superstitions which enslave them, and to solve the mysterious play of the forces of nature and rise to higher conceptions of truth of freedom and liberty. Within the great palisaded enclosure there is not one inch of space that does not vibrate with the wild life of the Igorrotes. Everything they make and use at home is made in the Village here, men fashioning keen spears and warlike head axes at a primitive forge, or weaving rattan into peculiar pocket hats which distinguish the Bontoc men from all other Islanders; men carving war shields with crude tools, and quiet turbaned men from Sebangan molding clay and brass pipes and ornamental metal chains. Women spinning and weaving cotton into the gaudy ""gee-strings"" worn by the warriors, as well as the gay cloths for their own simple but sufficient clothing; others beating and winnowing rice, and many of both sexes laboring in the remarkable "sementeras" which terrace the mountainside at the rear of the Village, where rice is grown under irrigation as practiced by them at home. All in all, it is the most extensive, interesting and amusing exhibit at the exposition."

properties.title: South Lake Union sawmills, ca. 1889
properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "This is an old-time picture showing the two mills which were build and operated at the south end of Lake Union in the early '80s. The mill in the foreground was erected late in 1881 and operated under various ownerships until comparatively recent years. It was quite generally known throughout its existence was the "Western Mill." David T. Denny, on whose original donation claim it was located, was for a time financially interested in its operation, cutting 25,000 feet daily. Later, in 1883, the second mill was built by a corporation with A. Brewster as President. It originally cut 40,000 feet daily. 'Lake Union' as the district became known, developed quite a little settlement, building largely around these mills, later augmented by a furniture factory, an ice plant, a brewery, two hotels and stores of various kinds. The first mill stood at what is now the intersection of Westlake Avenue with the lake shore. For some years after the mills started operation their supply of logs came from the timber on the shores of the lake itself. Later logs were drifted in from Lake Washington through the "ditch" which was dug between the two lakes of sufficient size to float logs."

Women spinning and weaving cotton into the gaudy ""gee-strings"" worn by the warriors, as well as the gay cloths for their own simple but sufficient clothing; others beating and winnowing rice, and many of both sexes laboring in the remarkable "sementeras" which terrace the mountainside at the rear of the Village, where rice is grown under irrigation as practiced by them at home. All in all, it is the most extensive, interesting and amusing exhibit at the exposition."

properties.title: Union and King Street Stations, ca. 1929Front
properties.description: During the early 1900's, there was an increasing press to connect railways with the city of Seattle. The high demand and competition between railways resulted in two railway stations being built directly next to each other at 4th Avenue and Jackson Street. King Street Station (seen at the far right) was constructed in 1906 and can be distinguished by its tower. Union Station, originally known as the Oregon and Washington Station, was not constructed until 1911. Both stations were sometimes referred to as ""union stations"" due to the fact that multiple railroad lines were shared within the same terminal. Alternative names for Union Station include the Union Depot and the Northern Pacific Great Northern Depot. Notes about the station's architecture can be found on the back of the postcard.

Left to right: Richard Carter, charged with killing his foster-mother; Ted Bradley, sentenced to died January 29 for killing a grocer in hold-up; Edward Evans, charged with shooting father; Julian Marcelino, (standing) who stabbed six persons to death and wounded thirteen others; Alfred Labored, Filipino murder suspect; and throwing an ace card down is John Zerfass, sentenced to life imprisonment for shooting and killing a drugless healer. Credit Line (ACME) 12/2/32."

properties.title: S.S. H.F. Alexander in dry dock at Seattle, March 11, 1923
properties.description: Constructed in 1915, the H.F. Alexander was originally known as the "Great Northern." It was used for naval service between 1917 and 1922. Afterwards it was converted to a passenger liner and its name was changed. The ship provided war service again from July 1942 to March 1946 under the name George S. Simonds. It was scrapped in February 1948. The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on March 11, 1923 with the caption: "Liner H.F. Alexander in Drydock. After dominating the scenery in the yard of the Todd Dry Docks, Inc., for several weeks, the Admiral Line's huge coastwise speed queen, H.F. Alexander, was returned to the water last week. The vessel's great prow rose to a height that commanded a full view of Harbor Island and the waterways. The photograph gives an idea of the long slender graceful build of the famous ship, her lines enabling her to make the speed that ranks her as being the fastest merchant vessel under the American flag. She will leave the yard March 21 or 22 and will return to the Admiral Line's Seattle-California route Tuesday March 27. She will return to service all tuned up and reconditioned for a great year in the coastwise passenger service."

properties.description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1511 ANDREW BAHR WILL SPEND FIRST VACATION IN FIVE YEARS AS COMMITTEEMAN OF THE NATIONAL TOURNAMENT AND OLYMPIC TRIALS. Seattle, Washington. - When a sailor gets his vacation he usually takes his best girl rowing on the park lake and just so a San Francisco police reported who had not had a relief from his boat in ten years took a vacation riding on the hurry-up wagon. Well Andrew Bahr, the great herder is going to follow along the same lines. His vacation has started and he is going to Mt. Rainier in a few days to supervise the running of the National Olympic trials which start next week. Photo shows Miss Frances Brown pinning the emblem of the Knights of the Skis. Direct Service .... 4/3/1935 ....."

properties.title: Men aboard seaplane at Sand Point Naval Station, July 21, 1934
properties.description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Watch your credit line: Photo from Wide World Photos: SEA: 1033 Six Navy Planes arrive in Seattle on Alaska flight. Seattle Washington. - Six of Uncle Sam's crack flying squadron were moored today after a flight from Southern California in what will be the first mass formation of a fleet of twelve planes to fly to that region. The flight purpose will be of great significance, as in defense of the Pacific Northwest. Photo shows officers and crew of the 7-P-I as they were being docked at Sand Point Seattle. Direct service ..... 7/21/34...."

properties.title: Lee Carr Durdan preparing taxidermied trophies for Prince Abdorreza Pahlavi, December 17, 1960
properties.description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Going to Iran: Lee Carr Durdan, taxidermist at Jonas Brothers here, worked on a mountain goad bagged in British Columbia by Prince Abdorreza Pahlavi of Iran. Jonas Brothers is preparing 40 hunt trophies to ship to the prince, who has returned to Iran after a North American hunting trip. Some of the trophies include, from upper left, a Bighorn sheep from Wyoming, a desert sheep bagged in Nevada, a stone sheep shot in British Columbia, an Alaskan doll sheep and, at lower left, a buffalo bagged in Wyoming." properties.title: "Dad" at U.S. Government Locks at Ballard, ca. 1920front
properties.description: Transcribed from postcard: "The Lake Washington Ship Canal, lying wholly within the limits of the City of Seattle, connects Puget Sound with a fresh water harbor comprising Salmon Bay, Lake Union, and Lake Washington and connecting waters with a total area of about 25,000 acres. A dam and two locks, one large and one small, about one mile from the Puget Sound entrance, hold the waters of the lakes 25 feet above extreme low water of Puget Sound. The large lock is 80 feet wide and will accommodate vessels with a maximum length of 760 feet and draft of 36 feet. The small lock is 150 feet long and 30 feet wide and will accommodate vessels with a draft of 16 feet. The spillway extending from the small lock to the south shore of Salmon Bay is 240 feel long with six spillway openings, each 32 feet long. A fish ladder for the passage of salmon to the spawning ground above the locks, and an opening for discharging salt water from the upper pool are provided through the dam. Total cost of construction was $5,000,000."

properties.title: Federal Building at 3rd Ave. and Union St., ca. 1910Front
properties.description: Street view of the Federal building in downtown Seattle (also known as the U.S. Court House, Custom House and Post Office). Construction on the Federal Building began in 1903 and ended in 1908. The building was located at the intersection of Union Street and Third Avenue, which was being regraded at the time. The Third Avenue regrade left a gap of four feet down to the new sidewalk which resulted in a new set of stairs being added to the building's exterior. The building was demolished in 1958.

properties.title: Anthony's Book Bindery, September 7, 1958Front
properties.description: This photo accompanied the September 7, 1958 Seattle Times article "This man lives in a house built before the fire of '89 and operates Seattle's Pioneer Bookbindery."" The photograph caption read: ""The Anthony Shop was built in 1905 in the back yard of the Anthony residence, built in 1887 on a lot purchase from A.A. Denny." The second half of the article is include on the back of the photograph. The 1958 City Directory lists the bindery at 1522 1/2 7th Ave.
